2. Docker Fundamentals
What is Docker

Docker is a containerization platform used to package applications and their dependencies into lightweight isolated containers.

Benefits:

consistent environments

fast deployment

efficient resource usage

portability across environments

3. Docker Architecture

Docker has several components.

Docker Engine

The core service responsible for:

building images

running containers

managing networking

Check Docker version:

docker version
Docker CLI

Command-line interface used to interact with Docker.

View available commands:

docker help
Docker Images

A Docker Image is a template used to create containers.

Search images in Docker Hub:

docker search ubuntu

This command shows:

image name

description

official image status

Docker Containers

A container is a running instance of an image.

Run Ubuntu container interactively:

docker run -it ubuntu

Explanation:

-it
interactive terminal

Docker assigns a random container name unless specified.

4. Running Containers

Run container in background:

docker run -itd ubuntu:latest

Explanation:

-d
detached mode

List running containers:

docker ps

List all containers:

docker ps -a

Attach to running container:

docker attach <container_id>

Exit container without stopping it:

CTRL + P + Q
5. Managing Containers

Stop container:

docker stop <container_id>

Start container:

docker start <container_id>

Pause processes inside container:

docker pause <container_id>

Resume container:

docker unpause <container_id>
6. Removing Containers Automatically

To automatically delete container when it stops:

docker run --rm ubuntu

This is useful for:

temporary containers

testing workloads

7. Naming Containers

Assign a container name:

docker run -it --name=mycontainer ubuntu

Benefits:

easier management

readable commands

8. Copy Files Between Host and Container

Copy files from container to host:

docker cp <container_id>:/path/file .

Example use cases:

debugging

retrieving logs

extracting artifacts

9. Docker Images and Collaboration

Create image from container:

docker commit <container_id> myimage

Export container as archive:

docker export <container_id> > container.tar

Used for:

collaboration

backup

migration

10. Tagging Images

Rename image:

docker tag ubuntu myubuntu

Tag images before pushing to registry.

11. Docker Registry

Log into Docker Hub:

docker login

Push image:

docker push username/image

Registries store container images.

Examples:

Docker Hub

AWS ECR

Google Container Registry

Azure Container Registry

12. Docker Daemon

Docker runs as a background service called the Docker daemon.

Check status:

service docker status

Start service:

service docker start

Stop service:

service docker stop
13. Docker Networking

Docker containers communicate through network drivers.

View networks:

docker network ls

Docker creates default networks.

Bridge Network

Default Docker network.

Allows communication between containers.

Uses the docker0 bridge interface.

Host Network

Container uses host networking stack.

Example:

docker run -it --network=host ubuntu

Characteristics:

no network isolation

container shares host IP

None Network

Container has no networking.

docker run -it --network=none ubuntu

Used for security or specialized workloads.

14. Network Namespace

Each container has its own network namespace.

This isolates:

IP address

routing table

network interfaces

View namespaces:

ip netns

Run command inside namespace:

ip netns exec <namespace> command
15. Virtual Ethernet Pair (veth)

Containers connect to the bridge using veth pairs.

A veth pair acts like a virtual cable:

container interface ↔ host interface

This allows communication between container and host network.

16. Port Mapping

Expose container ports to host.

Example:

docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx

Explanation:

8080 = host port
80 = container port

Check mapped ports:

docker port <container_id>
17. Docker Storage Overview

Containers are ephemeral.

Persistent data requires volumes.

Types:

bind mounts

docker volumes

tmpfs

Example volume:

docker volume create myvolume

Run container with volume:

docker run -v myvolume:/data ubuntu
18. Docker System Monitoring

Check disk usage:

docker system df

Verbose mode:

docker system df -v

Shows:

images

containers

volumes

reclaimable space

19. Docker Best Practices for SRE

Senior SREs should follow:

minimal base images

non-root containers

immutable infrastructure

container health checks

resource limits

Example production practices:

multi-stage builds

vulnerability scanning

signed images

CI/CD image builds

