21. Introduction to Kubernetes

Kubernetes is a container orchestration platform used to manage containerized applications.

It provides:

automatic scaling

self-healing

service discovery

rolling deployments

22. Kubernetes Core Components

Cluster consists of:

Control Plane

Manages cluster state.

Components:

API Server

Scheduler

Controller Manager

etcd database

Worker Nodes

Nodes run application containers.

Components:

kubelet

kube-proxy

container runtime

23. Kubernetes Pods

A Pod is the smallest deployable unit.

Create pod:

kubectl run nginx --image=nginx

List pods:

kubectl get pods

View logs:

kubectl logs <podname>
24. Kubernetes Deployments

Deployments manage pods and replicas.

View deployments:

kubectl get deploy

Apply deployment:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

View deployment manifest:

kubectl get deploy mydeploy -o yaml
25. Kubernetes Services

Services expose pods.

Types:

ClusterIP

NodePort

LoadBalancer

Example service creation:

kubectl apply -f service.yaml

Delete service:

kubectl delete svc <service-name>
26. Kubernetes Ingress

Ingress routes external traffic to services.

List ingress:

kubectl get ing

View details:

kubectl describe ing <name>

Ingress typically uses:

NGINX Ingress Controller

cloud load balancer

27. Kubernetes Namespaces

Namespaces group cluster resources.

List all namespaces:

kubectl get ns

View resources across namespaces:

kubectl get deploy -A

Important namespace:

kube-system

Contains Kubernetes core services.

28. Kubernetes Horizontal Scaling

Horizontal scaling increases number of pods.

Example:

3 pods → 10 pods

This improves:

throughput

availability

29. Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)

HPA scales pods automatically.

Example:

kubectl autoscale deployment php-apache --cpu-percent=50 --min=1 --max=10

Meaning:

scale pods when CPU > 50%
minimum pods = 1
maximum pods = 10

List autoscalers:

kubectl get hpa
30. Metrics Server

HPA requires metrics server.

Check deployment:

kubectl get deploy metrics-server -n kube-system

Metrics server provides:

CPU metrics

memory metrics

31. Load Testing Autoscaling

Generate load:

kubectl run -i --tty load-generator --rm --image=busybox --restart=Never -- /bin/sh -c "while sleep 0.01; do wget -q -O- http://php-apache; done"

This continuously sends requests to the service.

Monitor scaling:

kubectl get hpa
32. Resource Requests and Limits

Define container resources.

Example:

requests:
  cpu: 200m
  memory: 256Mi

limits:
  cpu: 500m
  memory: 512Mi

Requests = guaranteed resources
Limits = maximum allowed usage

33. Cluster Autoscaler

Cluster autoscaler adds new nodes when cluster resources are insufficient.

Example situation:

Pods require more CPU than cluster can provide
→ new nodes are added

Deploy autoscaler:

kubectl apply -f cluster-autoscaler.yaml
34. Checking Cluster Nodes

List nodes:

kubectl get nodes

Nodes provide infrastructure capacity for pods.

35. Debugging Kubernetes

Describe pod:

kubectl describe pod <podname>

Common errors:

CrashLoopBackOff
ImagePullBackOff
Insufficient CPU

View logs:

kubectl logs <podname>
36. Kubernetes Contexts

Check current cluster:

kubectl config current-context

List contexts:

kubectl config view

Contexts define which cluster kubectl communicates with.

37. Scaling Strategy for Senior SRE

Best practice is to combine:

Horizontal scaling → more pods
Vertical scaling → more nodes

Horizontal scaling improves performance.

Vertical scaling increases infrastructure capacity.
